        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2"  valign="top">
		<a name="50118"></a>
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;07/17/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 17:12:35</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=5685"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=5685')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=50118&amp;TOPIC_ID=6134&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=EQ+porting+to+Mac++%3B%2F&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>I really don't know if SOE/Verant has gone MAD or Crazy as a Fox. If it works it's a sucker bet that Verant will not pickup a LARGE number of Accounts.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Kinda makes ya wonder...</P><P>SOE/Verant's just another corporation whose executives are bonused by the same old traditional methods -- profit, profit, and profit.  And the way you increase profits are: increase revenue and/or decrease cost.  And I'll be dollars to donuts that their (EQ's) profit projection for FY2003 is nearly flat vs. FY2002.  Why?</P><P>Let's look at the FY2002 and FY2003 revenue picture for EQ: <BR>Subscriptions are the cash cow.  400K people paying $10-12/month, or about $45 million per year.  This year they've already increased the monthly fee by 20%, but this is a one time thing which will show it's profit growth only this fiscal year.  Do you think they're planning to raise fees by another 20% in FY2003?  Will your wife/husband/father/mother let you pay $15/month for EQ?  and $15 more for EQ2?  or EQOA? and &lt;gasp&gt; SWG?  On top of ISP, cable TV, etc. etc. My wife certainly won't!  <img src=icon_smile.gif border=0 align=middle></P><P>In fact, customer base probably shrunk some in FY2002 vs FY2001 (why did they stop showing server load by number of users just as DOAC came out?).  </P><P>Box sales are secondary, and maybe 30 to 40% of subscriptions.  SOL's box sales generated significant one-time cash flow (~$5 million the first week according to the SOE press kit or maybe $15 million total), it didn't necessarily increase their customer base by enough to compensate for increased operating costs.  For FY2003, they've got POP, but given its high-end nature, both initial and ongoing box sales will probably be less than SOL. </P><P>Other sources of income such as licensing, royalties?  No clue, but probably &lt; 1% of total given that they've got nothing technologically original going on (unlike Id software, for example).  Whoops, forgot about Fan Faire.  They probably do make a tidy sum on those.  Maybe 2-5% of revenue ($1-3 Million)?  </P><P>Which brings us to costs:<BR>They've added lots-n-lots of headcount, assets (servers), print marketing expense, more executives, a touring road show in a custom made bus with a fancy paint job (gawd that one must have cost a bloody fortune!), etc., etc.  What could possibly be next?  An EQ Blimp at the next X-Games?</P><P>So, no net increase in customer base and costs are now much higher with diminishing subscriber returns, means profits are lower.</P><P>They tried Legends.  Did it work?  I havne't seen any more like it.  They push char transfer and name change services almost weekly now.  How many people use it?  (at $100/hr per DBA do they get 2 transfers... that's gotta be 4000 transfers per year?)  These things are nice, but probalby are just barely covering the extra DBA/GM labor costs.</P><P>As the graphics/sound/db engines run out of steam, the cost of "upgrading" them with each new expansion goes up as the size of the entire game (i.e. geometrically).  Why no major advances in texture/bump mapping, algorythmic animations, hidden suface exclusion, Dot stacking, 15 buff limit -- this stuff is just not possible given the nature of their code design and resources they have available, which aren't otherwise occupied?</P><P>Occupied by what? you ask...</P><P>Scrambling to find a way to make more revenue the old fashioned way -- by focusing on their bread and butter -- i.e. increasing the customer base.  How do you do that with the same old game on the same old PC box?  You don't.  Instead, you change the game, change the box, and change (hopefully adding to) the user base: </P><P>1) MacEQ (won't cannabalize the EQ installed base at all).  This wasn't previously accounced probably because of the huge technical challenge and the cost of the resources required to pull it off.  They'll have half their brand new testing/quality control staff working on this one for 10 months!  They had to project the ROI, and I bet it wasn't an easy answer.  </P><P>2) EQOA (will not cannabalize EQ much).  But will allow new customers who don't have $2000 for a pc but have $300 for a console.  Exactly how many of those folks WANT to play games like EQ vs. Virtua Figher or Pickman or Tetris or ...?</P><P>3) SWG (will cannabalize EQ somewhat, but as an "experiential" game with less violence, it will appeal to a more broad customer base, read: women, &gt;30 adults, &lt;13 children).  IMO, this is the one that belongs on the console with (or in lieu of) EQOA.  I'd rather have my kids playing on a PS2 than screwing around with the same PC that we do our taxes on.</P><P>4) EQ2.  I bet this is the one the CFO at SOE likes the least, as it has the smallest long term ROI.  It only prevents them from losing customers, it won't gain them any market share at all.  So EQ is all sunk cost and has no long term ROI.  But since the customer base has put just as much effort into their characters as Verant has into the game... the transfer to EQ2 will be VERY SLOW.  That means supporting TWO games for a year or so with only ONE installed base.  Ouch!</P><P>5) Plain old advertising and discounting.  They've increased magazine ads -- ok so they're not idiots.  They've done discounts for long-term subscriptions -- good.  They've done a free 30-day trial subscription -- much better!</P><P>They've got a bunch of creative minds at Verant/SOE.  So there's gotta be lots more to come!  If there's a sliver of market out there, you can bet they're thinking about it.</P><P>I'm looking forward to seeing how all this works out.  Gonna be one hell of a business school case study when it's all over.</P><P><BR>- Gunkk <BR>...whose faction standing with Sony Online Entertainment has gotten worse.<BR>Level 36 Business School Graduate Wannabe<BR>The Penniless Server</P><P><BR>Edited by - Gunkk on 07/17/2002  17:23:01<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
